{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10177,"record_hash":"sha256:7e3bd8529d599d5e911eda9e7dd901c4da904f21e22cff5c8501d1daacf71e94","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:50:07.835Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 24dba5\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2106\nOutput:\nbut agentlog timeline sha256-9d942495afce65d863ef4d05e61ce2da --limit 20\n```\n\nJSON should include one entry per capture turn:\n\n- stable turn index within the session\n- `turn_key`\n- `previous_turn_key`\n- `capture_kind`\n- `captured_at`\n- `record_count`\n- record index range\n- environment snapshot status\n- observed branch/review/change target keys\n- first and last record timestamps\n- tiny previews of the first/latest user text and latest assistant final/status\n  text, when available\n- compact tool/command counts, when available\n\nThis command should not return full transcript records. It should stay cheap\nenough that an agent can run it before deciding what to read.\n\nWhen `--limit` returns only part of the session, the response must say so with\ncoverage metadata such as `showing_turns`, `total_turns`, `has_more_before`, and\n`has_more_after`. A receiving agent should not mistake the last 20 turns for the\nwhole session.\n\n### `records`\n\nPurpose: answer \"show me the actual transcript records for this turn.\"\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog records sha256-9d942495afce65d863ef4d05e61ce2da \\\n  --turn [REDACTED:entropy] \\\n  --from end \\\n  --limit 200\n```\n\nJSON should return:\n\n- `session_key`\n- `turn_key`\n- turn metadata\n- ordered transcript records\n- record index/range metadata\n- `next` and `previous` cursors or offsets when more records are available\n\nThe command must be bounded by default. Backfilled turns can contain thousands\nof records, so `records` should never accidentally dump a whole historical\nsession because one turn was large. If the agent needs more, it can read the\nnext or previous range.\n\n`--from end` should be the default. For handoff, the latest records in a huge\nbackfill are usually more useful than the oldest records. The oldest records can\nstill matter for the original task prompt, so `--from start` should remain\navailable.\n\nEven when reading from `end`, return records in natu\n[TRUNCATED]\nranch. Some are\nsidecar/subagent review sessions, not the main user thread.\n\nThe handoff layer should not hide these. It should make them legible:\n\n- main-looking sessions: long-running, many incremental turns, latest user asks\n- sidecar-looking sessions: one backfill, review prompt, separate provider\n  session id, often created close together\n- compacted/resumed sessions: may have a new provider session id but overlapping\n  prior conversation context\n\nAvoid hard-coding those labels until the source data supports them. For now,\nexpose enough facts for the consuming agent to decide.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no provider-native resume\n- no generated persistent handoff summary\n- no magic `handoff` command for v1\n- no durable inferred ownership like \"this branch belongs to this session\"\n- no GitButler app API dependency for the first flow\n- no automatic transcript dumping into `but status`\n- no product-specific review browsing payloads\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Do we need a first-class \"session outline\" primitive in `but-agentlog`, or can\n  it be assembled cheaply from existing reads?\n- Can we reliably capture provider metadata that distinguishes top-level\n  sessions from spawned subagents?\n- Should compaction/resume grouping be a later derived feature, or do we need to\n  store more source metadata now to make it possible?\n- How much transcript text should human-readable output show by default?\n\n## Recommended First Implementation Slice\n\nDo not implement \"handoff\" as one magic command.\n\nFirst add enough generic CLI read commands that an agent or skill can perform the\ncatch-up workflow:\n\n1. enhance `agentlog sessions` so JSON includes session outline fields, not just\n   keys\n2. add a bounded timeline command for one session\n3. add a bounded records command for one turn\n4. write a small skill/workflow note that tells agents how to use those commands\n\nThat keeps the feature honest. If the workflow feels clumsy after using the\nprimitives on real branches, improve the primitives rather than hiding them\nbehind an opaque command.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:50:07.835Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}